Relevant for senior software and data engineers, the Dremel paper explains how Google performs ad-hoc queries on massive data sets . For example, a product manager may want to query: Find the number of people who live in Bengaluru, travel often, and search for cars. How do you run these queries efficiently? Google Dremel takes advantage of this access pattern: most statistics queries are aggregates like sum, min, max, count . If we store our data in a column-oriented format , running aggregate queries is fast. Dremel is excellent for storing and fetching aggregates. It's also got an optimiser that chooses an execution path (similar to traditional SQL databases). The difference is, Dremel can run on thousands of nodes ! This requires Dremel to useÂ interesting algorithms like Finite Automata and a version of Segment Trees (yeah, you read it right). Dremel has been called as one of the most influential papers in recent times (it's been an inspiration for systems like Apache Impala). It also won the Test of Time award at VLDB 2020 .
